<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - FULLER 10 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS - INSTALL - AUXILIARY
        COUNTERSHAFT BEARING SHIM PROCEDURE
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="install" graphiccount="2">
        <title>AUXILIARY COUNTERSHAFT BEARING SHIM PROCEDURE</title>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Use genuine Eaton replacement gaskets for the auxiliary housing and countershaft bearing cover. Do
                    not omit the gaskets. Bearing endplay is influenced by the compressed thickness of the gasket (.28
                    to .30 mm or .011 to .012 inch).
                </para>
            </caution>
            <note>
                <para>The bearing endplay must be checked and adjusted any time a countershaft, bearing, or housing is
                    replaced. If, during reassembly, the same countershaft, bearings, housing, and shims are re-used and
                    kept in the same location, it is not necessary to reset bearing endplay.
                </para>
            </note>
            <note>
                <para>The following procedure is used to adjust the endplay for the auxiliary countershaft tapered
                    bearings. By correctly following this procedure, each countershaft will have .03 to .13 mm (.001 to
                    .005 inch) endplay.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the auxiliary countershaft bearing covers and shims. Clean all old gasket material
                from the gasket mounting surfaces on the countershaft bearing covers and the auxiliary housing.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Make sure that the auxiliary section is in gear by rotating the output yoke. The
                countershafts must rotate. If they do not rotate, move the range yoke bar either forward or backward to
                engage the auxiliary section in either high or low range.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clean and lightly oil the threads of two countershaft bearing cover bolts. Thread these
                bolts into two opposing bolt holes in the housing. They must thread in easily. If necessary, run an
                M10x1.5 tap into the holes to clean the threads (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f13032g2">Figure 162</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f13032g2" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/G13032G2.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 162. Run Tap into Holes</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the .100 inch gauging shim included with the shim parts kit, and then install rear
                bearing cover, evenly threading in the two cleaned bolts. Do not install the gasket at this time.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Evenly tighten the two bolts to 7 in-lbs. The gap between the shim tool and the housing
                surface should be even from side to side.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>7 in-lbs. is slightly more than finger tight. Do not overtighten the bolts. If the bolts are too
                    tight, the bearing cover will become distorted.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Rotate the output shaft 4 times clockwise and 4 times counterclockwise. The rotation will
                seal and align the rollers in each tapered bearing. Retighten the bolts to 7 in-lbs. If the
                countershafts do not rotate, the range sliding clutch is in neutral. Shift the range clutch to either
                high or low range.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge to measure the gap between the rear bearing cover and the auxiliary
                housing gasket surface. Measure and record the gap at both bolt locations (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f13032g3">Figure 163</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f13032g3" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/G13032G3.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 163. Measure and Record Gap</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Average the two feeler gauge measurements by adding the measurements together and dividing
                by 2.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Locate the feeler gauge average measurement in the shim chart,
                <hotlnk xrefid="t1303201">Table 1</hotlnk>, to determine the required shim and color code.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The oil pump shim is used when an auxiliary oil pump or PTO is mounted on the countershaft. The
                    oil pump shims have a smaller outside diameter.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the rear bearing cover.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the shim and place a new gasket around the auxiliary countershaft bore.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply Loctite 242 or equivalent to the auxiliary countershaft rear bearing cover bolts and
                auxiliary countershaft rear bearing cover.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the auxiliary countershaft rear bearing cover and secure it with the bolts. Make
                sure the shim is in proper location and is not pinched between the cover and the housing. Tighten the
                bolts to 54 to 61 Nm (40 to 45 ft-lbs).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Use a thick grease to hold the shim in position when installing the cover.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Repeat this procedure for the remaining countershaft.</para>
        </step1>
